    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "that makes sense, i think. so whats the deal with that \"spooky action at a distance\" thing i keep hearing about? is that just a way to describe the connection, or is there something actually weird or unexplained about how it works?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "The \"spooky action at a distance\" phrase was coined by Einstein, who was skeptical of entanglement. He felt that it was too strange, too unexplainable, and that it went against our classical intuition of space and time. But, in a way, that's exactly what makes entanglement so fascinating.\n\nWhen two particles are entangled, measuring the state of one particle instantly affects the state of the other, regardless of the distance between them. This is what Einstein called \"spooky action at a distance,\" because it seems to defy the idea that information can travel faster than light.\n\nHowever, it's not that the connection itself is weird or unexplained; it's more that our current understanding of space and time doesn't allow for it. Entanglement is a fundamental aspect of quantum mechanics, and it's been experimentally confirmed countless times.\n\nThink of it like a game of hide-and-seek with a group of skilled players. They can communicate with each other instantly, no matter how far apart they are, but they're not actually sending information through space. It's more like they're all connected by a shared intuition, a kind of \"gut feeling\" that lets them know what the other players are doing",
      "source": "target",
